# System Architectures — Complete Reference Guide

ArchTemplat v1.0 · 32 Major World Architectures

---

## 1. Monolithic Architecture
All components (UI, logic, database) are in one single deployable unit. Simple to start with but hard to scale. Best for small teams and early-stage projects.

## 2. Layered (N-Tier) Architecture
The app is split into layers — Presentation, Business, Persistence, and Database. Each layer talks only to the one below it. Common in enterprise applications.

## 3. Microservices Architecture
The app is broken into small independent services, each doing one thing. They communicate over HTTP or messaging. Used by Netflix, Amazon, and Uber.

## 4. Service-Oriented Architecture (SOA)
Similar to microservices but services are bigger and communicate through a central Enterprise Service Bus (ESB). Common in large enterprise environments.

## 5. Serverless Architecture (FaaS)
You write functions, the cloud runs them when triggered. No server management. You pay only when your code runs. Good for event-driven or unpredictable workloads.

## 6. Event-Driven Architecture (EDA)
Services communicate by sending and listening to events through a broker like Kafka or RabbitMQ. Services are fully decoupled from each other.

## 7. Hexagonal Architecture (Ports & Adapters)
The core business logic sits in the middle, completely isolated. Everything external (UI, DB, APIs) connects through defined ports. Very testable and flexible.

## 8. Clean Architecture
By Robert C. Martin. Code is organized in circles — the inner circles (entities, use cases) know nothing about the outer ones (frameworks, UI). Dependencies always point inward.

## 9. Domain-Driven Design (DDD)
By Eric Evans. The design is built around the business domain with a shared language between developers and business people. Uses concepts like Bounded Contexts and Aggregates.

## 10. CQRS + Event Sourcing
CQRS splits reading and writing into separate models. Event Sourcing stores every change as an event instead of just saving the current state. Great for audit and history.

## 11. Pipe and Filter Architecture
Data passes through a series of processing steps (filters) connected by pipes. Each filter transforms the data. Used in ETL pipelines, compilers, and Unix commands.

## 12. Space-Based Architecture
Removes the database as a bottleneck by using an in-memory distributed data grid. Built for extreme scalability. Used in high-traffic and real-time systems.

## 13. Broker / Message Bus Architecture
A central broker (like RabbitMQ or Kafka) routes messages between services. Services only talk to the broker, never directly to each other.

## 14. Peer-to-Peer (P2P) Architecture
No central server. Every node acts as both a client and a server. Used in file sharing (BitTorrent) and blockchain networks (Bitcoin, Ethereum).

## 15. Client-Server Architecture
The most basic pattern. Clients send requests, servers respond. Can be 2-tier, 3-tier, or N-tier depending on how many layers are in between.

## 16. Master-Slave Architecture
A master node distributes work to slave nodes and collects the results. Used for database replication and parallel processing. Examples: MySQL, Redis, Hadoop.

## 17. Shared-Nothing Architecture
Every node has its own CPU, memory, and storage. Nothing is shared between nodes. Makes horizontal scaling very easy. Used by Cassandra and CockroachDB.

## 18. Lambda Architecture (Big Data)
Handles big data with two paths running in parallel — a batch layer for historical data and a speed layer for real-time data. Both are merged in a serving layer.

## 19. Kappa Architecture (Big Data)
A simpler version of Lambda. Only one streaming pipeline handles everything. You reprocess old data by replaying the stream. Uses Kafka and Flink.

## 20. Data Mesh Architecture
Each team owns and manages their own data like a product. Data ownership is decentralized, following the same idea as microservices but applied to data.

## 21. Microfrontend Architecture
Applies microservices thinking to the frontend. Each team builds and deploys their own piece of the UI independently. Different teams can use different frameworks.

## 22. JAMstack Architecture
JavaScript + APIs + Markup. Pages are pre-built at build time and served from a CDN. Dynamic features are handled by JavaScript and external APIs at runtime.

## 23. BFF — Backend for Frontend
A separate backend is built for each type of client (mobile, web, TV). Each BFF returns exactly the data that client needs, nothing more.

## 24. SAGA Pattern Architecture
Manages transactions that span multiple microservices. Instead of one big transaction, it runs a chain of small ones. If something fails, compensating actions undo the previous steps.

## 25. Strangler Fig Architecture
A migration pattern. You slowly replace parts of a legacy system with new services. Traffic is gradually shifted until the old system is completely replaced.

## 26. Cell-Based Architecture
The system is split into isolated cells, each with its own app, database, and cache. If one cell fails, the others keep running. Used for high availability.

## 27. Edge Computing Architecture
Processing happens close to the user at edge nodes (like CDN servers) instead of in a central data center. Reduces latency. Used for IoT and real-time apps.

## 28. Reactive Architecture
Based on the Reactive Manifesto. Systems are built to be Responsive, Resilient, Elastic, and Message-Driven. Built for high availability and async communication.

## 29. Actor Model Architecture
The actor is the basic unit. Each actor has its own private state and communicates only through messages. No shared state means no race conditions. Used in Erlang and Akka.

## 30. Plugin / Extension Architecture
A core system exposes an API for plugins. Third parties extend the system without touching the core code. Examples: VS Code, WordPress, Jenkins.

## 31. API Gateway Architecture
One entry point for all client requests. The gateway handles authentication, rate limiting, logging, SSL, and routing to the right backend service.

## 32. Service Mesh Architecture
A dedicated infrastructure layer manages all communication between services. Each service gets a sidecar proxy that handles traffic, security, and observability. Examples: Istio, Linkerd.

---

## When to Use What

**By team size:**
- 1 to 5 developers — Monolithic or Layered
- 5 to 20 developers — SOA or Modular Monolith
- 20 to 100 developers — Microservices, EDA, DDD
- 100+ developers — Cell-Based, Data Mesh

**By domain:**
- E-Commerce — Microservices, SAGA, BFF
- Analytics — Lambda, Kappa, Data Mesh
- Real-time / IoT — EDA, Edge, Reactive
- Finance / Banking — CQRS, DDD, SOA

**By concern:**
- Need fault tolerance — Cell-Based, Reactive
- Need full audit history — Event Sourcing, CQRS
- Need to scale fast — Serverless, Shared-Nothing
- Need team independence — Microservices, Microfrontend
- Migrating a legacy system — Strangler Fig
